		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Tam prudenter, qu&agrave;m
						temperanter. Qui plurimum habet Viri,
						minim&egrave; omnium effoeminatur.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				As prudently as temperately. He who has the majority of a man is least unmanned of all.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cedat Cupido Cupidini, humanus diuino: et vincat Venerem Venus, coelestis terrestr&egrave;.
						Da mihi artium Cupidinem flagrantissimum: et Virtutum dulcissimam Venerem.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Desire gives way to desire, the human [gives way] to the divine; and love conquers love, the heavenly [conquers] the terrestrial.
				Give me the most burning desire for the arts and the sweetest love of virtue.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Homo venereus, non nisi dimidium hominis. Euscopius, et Megalander.)
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Euscopus"/> <!--JG: I think Euscopius is a variant of Euscopus, one of Harvey's characters-->
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A desirous man is only half a man. Euscopius and a high-souled man.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Post quinquagesimum, omnis Coitus perniciosus. Domat indomitos; Eq[uo]s, tauros, vrsos.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				After the fifty-fifth year, all coitus is pernicious. It conquers the unconquerable: horses, bulls, bears.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Veneris nescius, Phoenix: tam actor Solis,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						qua[m] auis Solis.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A phoenix knows nothing of love. As an actor of the sun, so a bird of the sun.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
